<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>The above principle means that even people sharing the represented knowledge may not be the suitable person for summarizing the representation because they may not have the knowledge of representation.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>This is because the establishment of rich social relations indicates common individual characteristics and social characteristics.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>However, authors have limited time and may be influenced by individual characteristics (e.g., health and mood, and worldview) and social characteristics (e.g., culture, economy and influence).</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>The openness principle implies that establishing static criteria for evaluating summarization is unnecessary, and that a closed system is incapable for reaching a satisfied summary.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>The person who shares the represented knowledge and the knowledge for representation is suitable for summarization.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>Observing and rethinking the basic characteristics of human language use can inspire research on summarization as language use including listening, speaking, reading, writing, understanding, and thinking.</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>(5) Transforming summarizations into the problem of searching suitable persons or summaries in the social networks of authors, readers, summarizers, representations and links.</a>
<a name="7">[7]</a> <a href="#7" id=7>The suitable summarizer for summarizing a representation is rendered by the social network of its writers and readers.</a>
<a name="8">[8]</a> <a href="#8" id=8>Ranking reviews to encourage contribution and competition among reviews reflect social value in a summarization environment.</a>
<a name="9">[9]</a> <a href="#9" id=9>The problem of designing a suitable summarizer can be transformed into the problem of searching a suitable summarizer in cyberspace.</a>
<a name="10">[10]</a> <a href="#10" id=10>(4) Enabling different summaries to cooperate and compete with each other for impact at multiple dimensions (e.g., acceptance for reading and adoption for generating new summaries).</a>
<a name="11">[11]</a> <a href="#11" id=11>(2) Knowledge for representation (e.g., grammars and idioms) and knowledge to be represented (e.g., scientific knowledge) are separated.</a>
<a name="12">[12]</a> <a href="#12" id=12>This is because the represented knowledge was shared and the knowledge for representation is at the same level.</a>
